General Accident (GA), the leading British insurer, estimated yesterday that its losses 
from Hurricane Andrew might reach $40 million; however, GA has only a half-percent 
share of the Florida market and the estimate is based on the assumption that GA's
catastrophe insurance would be triggered by the extensive claims. The company's loss 
adjustors guess that losses to all insurers might exceed $8 billion. Other insurers have 
estimated that losses from the storm that hit Florida and Louisiana might be anywhere 
from $1 billion to $20 billion. At this time no one is certain of the extent of losses.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d067"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT923-6110"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Hurricane Andrew hit southern Florida Monday morning, was moving north-west across 
the Gulf of Mexico yesterday, and now threatens New Orleans and the coast from 
Mississippi to Texas. At least three people were killed by the storm in the Bahamas 
Sunday and twelve in Florida Monday. Two million people have been advised to move 
from the threatened coastal areas. Although it is too early to assess the cost of the 
storm, one official estimates $15 billion to $20 billion of damage already. Most of the 
insurance claims from damage in Florida and Louisiana will be filed with State Farm, 
Allstate, and American International Group insurance companies.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d067"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT923-5797"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Hurricane Andrew, which killed 15 people and left a quarter of a million people 
homeless in south Florida, hit sparsely populated farming communities and swampland 
in Louisiana killing two people and injuring less than 100. Most Louisiana oil refineries 
were not affected. In Florida local officials were critical of delays in supplying food, 
drinking water, and other supplies to thousands in need. Transportation Secretary 
Andrew Card promised "dramatic" improvements within 24 hours and President Bush 
ordered troops to Florida. The government estimated it would cost $20 billion to $30 
billion to rebuild in Florida and care for those displaced by the storm.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d067"
