SUMMARIZER="A">

Last night U.S. cities along the Gulf of Mexico from Alabama to eastern Texas were on 
storm watch for Hurricane Andrew which early yesterday caused at least eight deaths 
and heavy property damage in southern Florida.  Florida Power estimates that 1.2 
million of its customers are without power. There was concern last night that the 
hurricane might hit New Orleans which is especially vulnerable because of its low-lying 
location. It could also threaten offshore oil production facilities along the Gulf coast of 
Louisiana and Texas. A British insurance adjuster estimates that total losses, 
concentrated among U. S. Insurers, could exceed $15 billion.</SUM>


<SUM
DOCSET="d067"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT923-6038"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Hurricane Andrew yesterday smashed its way through Louisiana causing heavy 
damage in rural communities but missing low-lying New Orleans. After hitting Louisiana 
with winds up to 120 miles per hour, Andrew lost force and by yesterday afternoon was 
down-graded to a tropical storm. Early reports indicate one death, 75 injuries, and 
thousands homeless in Louisiana after 14 deaths in Florida and three in the Bahamas. 
Across Florida 2 million people were without electricity yesterday. There was more than 
$15 billion property damage in Florida, but most of it was to uninsured property, so 
insurers' losses are likely to total less than $1 billion.</SUM>


<SUM
DOCSET="d067"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT923-5589"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="A">

Both Hurricane Andrew and a dollar crisis blew themselves out this week. Most of the 
damage from the dollar crisis came a week ago Friday and the following Monday when 
bond yields jumped sharply and the Dow Jones average dropped by more than 75 
points. The dollar dropped to DM 1.40, the lowest ever against the D-mark after buildup 
over the summer in the difference between U. S. and German interest rates. The effect 
of Hurricane Andrew on Wall Street was not surprising. The stocks of insurance 
companies with the greatest exposure in southern Florida tumbled while those of home 
construction companies showed sharp gains.</SUM> 
